The ref to `String::compareTo` is a special kind of method reference called [&quot;Reference to an Instance Method of an Arbitrary Object of a Particular Type&quot;](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/methodreferences.html).

In this case, the compiler knows that we are referencing a not-static method of a given class, and it can translate to a functional interface with the desired signature. 

For example:

```java
String t1 = &quot;t1&quot;;
String t2 = &quot;t2&quot;;

// this
Comparator&lt;String&gt; comparator = String::compareTo;
comparator.compareTo(t1, t2);

// will be &#39;translated&#39; to:
Comparator&lt;String&gt; comparator = (String s1, String s2) -&gt; s1.compareTo(s2);
t1.compareTo(t2);

```

&gt; Note that the method will be called with the context of the first parameter (the this used will be `t1`).

Points 8 and 9 of [State of lambda](http://cr.openjdk.java.net/%7Ebriangoetz/lambda/lambda-state-final.html) give a rationale for this implementation.


From [Overview of method references][1] youtube video

[![Overview of method references][2]][2]


  [1]: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4bykHgnNXuA
  [2]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/WklGq.png

